Promoting EVs in India will bring huge energy insecurity,  increase significantly import bill and unemployment.
Motors,  majority of parts and batteries of EVs are imported from China.
India has no resources reserves and production of essential materials for li ion batteries. 
About 50% parts of EVs are made locally, rest are imported from China.  
Except Nexon and TIGOR, all electric vehicles are Zero to 2 stars GNCAP crash rated.
50% of power stations generate electricity use imported fossil fuels. 

Ultra low emission BS6 compliant vehicles and fuels have been successfully adopted and implemented in India already.

उत्तर प्रदेश की सोशल इंजीनियरिंग: 
        1.  श्री राम एवं भगवान शिव के अनुयायी:  उत्तर प्रदेश को केवल ऐसे  मुख्य मंत्रियों,  सांसदों,  विधायकों,  एवं प्रशासनिक अधिकारियों की जरूरत है,  जो श्री राम एवं भगवान शिव के आर्दशों का ही निर्वहन करते हों,  गऊ रक्षक हों,  और वे उत्तर प्रदेश के  15%  ब्राम्हणों,  या  13%  ठाकुरों में से ही हों।
        2.  गैर-ब्राम्हण,  या  गैर-ठाकुर मतदाता:  लेकिन उत्तर प्रदेश में गैर-ब्राम्हण,  या  गैर-ठाकुर मतदाताओं    का बहुमत भी है।  उदाहरण के लिए   22% मुस्लिम,        17% जाटव,  13% यादव,  10% चमार,  3% पासी,   2% आदिवासी,  5% धोबी+कोरी+बालमीकि।  जबकि उत्तर प्रदेश की कुल जनसंख्या 20.42 करोड़ है।
        3.  बेटी पढ़ाओ बेटी बचाओ:  वे चाहते हैं कि उनकी बेटियों और महिलाओं को घर से बाहर निकलने की पूर्ण आजादी हो,  और वे अच्छी तरह से शिक्षित हो सकें,  और उन्हें विज्ञान,  और प्रौद्योगिकी में विश्व स्तर की शिक्षा मिल सके।
        4.  किसान के उत्पाद की लागत:  वे उनकी फसल का उचित समर्थन मूल्य निर्धारित किया जाना चाहते हैं, और  अगर उन्हें तब भी नुकसान पहुँचता है,  तो उनके नुकसान की भरपाई चाहते हैं।  बिजली:  वे मुफ्त बिजली चाहते हैं,  या रियायती दरों पर।  
        5.  जातियों का कुल योग%:  15%+13%+22%+17%+13%+10%+3%+2%+5%=100%,  क्रमश:।

Wind and solar EROI is grave. Wind and solar and battery sized to near full-economy magnitude is a no-go, with EROI approaching 1, that is comparable or more energy invested in manufacturing in China than we can practically harves during the systems' lifetime (and battery is a big part of that). Nuclear is the only clean energy with high EROI (>70, fast neutron reactors EROI>150) and low amount of pollution and waste when sized to near full-economy magnitude. "Renewables" gets us to the energy cliff and resource crisis, devastating to our economy, civilization and the environment.

So what you are saying is. we need to use Nuclear power to generate the power to make these vehicles? Yes I agree!

Also you can't sit around waiting for battery tech to be optimized before deciding its a good idea. I agree battery tech isn't where we need it to be but if there was no demand for mass production of batteries, then we would never get to a place where there is a demand for more efficient manufacturing and recycling of battery tech. We've been sitting on the same old battery tech for over 100 years because there was no reason to optimize it's production.

During that time we've seen extreme booms in petrol engines (thanks to the fuel crisis in the 80s). Massive advancements in computer tech, thanks to massive demands in computing needs and smart phone development. And now I feel like its finally time to develop battery tech and unfortunately its going to have to come at the expense of a few years of inefficient battery manufacturing to be able to get to a place where we can be happy with the results of our battery tech.

Even investing in hybrids won't get us where we need to be in that department because batteries aren't the primary power source in those power units. All we achieve with hybrids is defer the research and development of batteries, while we making a profit from using petrol as a main power source. 

Sorry for the rant (if anyone is even reading it) but I think it's important that we have these years of uphill battles before our huge battery tech discovery. I'm not saying we shouldn't challenge it, but we need to be optimistic of the implications for the future and encourage development of what could be our next big discovery in humanity thus far.

I think the horse / corvette comparison is deeply flawed.  The claim is that, since the the CO2 produced by the horse is consumed by grass, and grass transforms the CO2 into oxygen, and the oxygen is consumed by the horse, that the horse is not adding CO2 to the air.  The CO2 from the corvette can also be consumed by grass, and transformed into Oxygen.  Oxygen is an element that we do not currently have a problem with over abundance of.  However, one could argue that the Corvette uses Oxygen during the combustion process to generate energy and CO2, so the Corvette also has that same "cycle".  

Both the horse and the corvette add CO2 to the air.  The claim is also made that, given the same mileage, a horse emits more CO2 than a corvette.  What is missing here is that a horse is much slower than a corvette, and requires much more rest.  A person using a horse for transportation would likely travel much less mileage than a person with a corvette.  So, no, a horse will not typically produce more CO2 than a corvette, unless the person driving the Corvette is going extremely slow and for only a short distance.

Certainly they would change if it were, say, a horse, not an EV, being compared. I.e. why do we necessarily assume an EV should behave exactly the same as an ICEV? 2. The operational lifespan of an EV isn’t the same as an ICEV—fewer moving parts means much longer lifespan, even counting for the lifespan of the battery itself (noted by others). 3. The end-of-life energy use is not considered: how much energy is needed to process/recycle an EV vs. ICEV? This isn’t to say the conclusions are necessary incorrect, but the analysis does not look at the whole picture and makes certain assumptions about how to correctly compare two vehicle types, which is exactly the problem the analysis claims to overcome. I’m therefore left completely unconvinced by the analysis, regardless of the end conclusion (that more renewables are needed in the grid for EVs to have lower GHG emissions overall than ICEVs).

Fact, our atmosphere is a bit more than 20% oxygen, or 200,000 parts per million.  Fact, our atmosphere is approximately 416 parts per million CO2, or about 0.0416%.  This is up from estimates 200 years ago of about 300 PPM.  So yes, we have seen a significant increase over past levels. This presentation is very selective in the information used and omits numerous other considerations to present a fairly biased viewpoint.  It doesn't consider the role that BEVs will start to play shortly in smart-grid evolution, as new features like vehicle to grid (V2G) become standard on new cars turning them all into virtual power plants. This will make BEVs pivotal in enabling faster transition to renewable energy by stabilising grid supply from otherwise unreliable generation sources, like solar and wind, making them more viable baseload generation solutions. We now have car companies like Volvo providing CO2 figures for the entire lifecycle, cradle to grave, of their ICE and BEV cars which show the BEVs are considerably lower in CO2 compared to an ICE car driven for equal distances over the life of the car. 
It has also been shown that the latest BEVs have now reached levels of efficiency that even if powered entirely from coal generated electricity, they still contribute less CO2 than an ICE car of equivalent class, driving the same distance. Granted we still couldn't push the button today anyway,  as we physically do not have the electricity generation capacity to swap every car.  But given solar and wind are now much cheaper per MWh than any other generation source, to not mandate a transition to a green energy economy with BEVs underpinning the grid would be like placing shackles around the feet of your economy.  Yes, it's going to cost to transition, but the sooner you reach that pivot point the benefit potential will be enormous.  The only people to benefit from sticking with the status quo are fossil fuel companies.

Assuming Graham Conway's CO2 numbers are correct, which I cannot do because of the lack of references and scientific support, Graham does a disservice to himself and anyone who walks away from the TEDx Talk or this video thinking that the only metric by which vehicle propulsion fuels should be measured is CO2. Internal combustion engines don't just emit CO2; they also emit criteria pollutants such as oxides of nitrogen, sulfur dioxide, and carbon monoxide and airborne toxics such as formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, acrolein, benzene, 1,3- butaidene, and, in the case of diesel engines, a highly toxic particulate matter. Criteria pollutants cause billions of dollars a year in damage to crops and human health (asthma for one). Airborne toxics lead to thousands of additional cases of cancer and death annually. Additionally, Graham fails to address the energy security issue associated with fossil fuels. The U.S. produces enough petroleum products to be self-sufficient, but in a global economy, producers will sell those products to the highest bidder, and that will not always be us. The Russian invasion of Ukraine shows how Germany's reliance on Russian natural gas affected worldwide markets. Were more of Germany's (and Western Europe's) vehicles fueled by domestically produced renewable energy, Russia would have no bargaining power. Which brings us to jobs. Domestically produced electricity will create many times more jobs than are created by the fossil fuel industry.

The potential for EVs to support the electrical grid is much larger than is presented here. However, the key to maximizing EVs as a grid resource is the use of intermediary batteries.  By 2030, it may be common for the average single family home to have 50-100 kwh of home energy storage (2-3 days-worth of electricity).  Such households simply charge their home batteries during the time when electricity is cheapest and then use the electricity whenever they want to, including deploying the power from their home batteries to their EVs.  If you have even just 25-30% of households with that kind of arrangement, electricity utilities will be able to deploy substantial renewable energy at low cost without having to worry about curtailment.

What is always good value at Costco is their Kirkland brand dog food.  Most people don't know that Kirkland brand dog kibble is made by a high end dog food manufacturer. The dog food manufacturer makes food for brands that may cost $100 per bag or more (that bag being smaller than the one you'd buy at Costco).  Therefore it is very good value indeed.  Plus, it is a good quality dog food despite the cost. Giant breed owners are very picky about what they feed their dogs because with giant breeds, good nutrition is important. We've always fed our giant breeds on Kirkland dog food and know many giant breed owners that do too.    Our dogs get through a LOT of kibble and with Kirkland we can afford it much more easily. Recently, one of my dogs, being elderly has had to move to  a different kind of kibble that is hydrolized protein so we can't feed her the Kirkland brand.  That different kibble is made by that same high end food manufacturer under their own name, and I'm paying nearly $100 per 25 pound bag!  I'm feeling the pain, let me tell you! Our other dog remains on the Kirkland Nature's Domain salmon. In surveys of dog foods, the Kirkland brand always comes out near to the top as being one of the best.  So I absolutely recommend it especially for people with large and giant breeds who get through a lot of food every week.

Their nuts (peanuts, cashews, mixed) are excellent. But you get a lot in the container. And they don't keep very well for long periods of time after they've been opened. However, if you put them in a vac sealed bag or even a zip lock laid flat, they'll fit in the freezer very easily and stay fresh until you need them (let them thaw completely before eating)!! Furthermore, if they do get a bit rancid or stale, put them in the air fryer at 350 for 5 mins and then remove and let cool completely. Yeh Daddy! A tip from the Culinary Camper: Jean Flambeau!

On the olive oil. Stick with when they have the 1 liter bottles from various regions of Italy. The good news is this is very high quality olive oil and not a blend from other countries around the Mediterranean. One favorite of mine is the one that says it's from Bitonto Italy. This is a small town outside of Bari on the Adriatic side of Italy. We visited the actual press and supplier for this olive oil on a trip a few years back and saw them pressing the olive oil. A great treat. We even bought some and carried it back on the plane with us. The ONLY thing I don't like is by the time the oil is pressed, packaged and shipped to Costco around the world, it's already a year old, which means it's not the absolutely freshest oil. To get that you would have to order directly from a company which we also do yearly. But as for olive oil in Costco, stick to the 1 liter bottles when they arrive in your store and not the big plastic jugs. Enjoy!  Ciao.

Soo, as a Costco Supervisor, there are some things you aren’t necessarily explaining well. The .88 is a directors price because we only have one item left and we need to get rid of it to make room for other seasonal stuff. The director makes the decision and does not need to reduce the price if he or she decides not to. Also, you need to understand that most of what we sell is sold at the same price we bought it at. Hense why we don’t sell multiple brands for one item. So for example, we won’t sell 3 brands of ketchup. Why? Larger bulk means cheaper for Costco and cheaper for the member. Another thing, companies will pay to have their products on display at the front fence and food stands, we don’t actually put them because they’re full price. Chances are we’re actually selling those products at the same price we bought them at. You need know that our membership sales are what keeps the store running. They pay the employees and a lot more in our stores.

Mostly accurate, just a few observations:

Secret #2: The rental rate may not always be as attractive as going through broker, but usually T&C are much more relaxed and prices of additional equipment and services are much lower. Depending on Your needs, renting directly through provider can be cheaper. Rental companies have their own reservation teams, don't be afraid to ask them anything, email is the best way of communication.

Secret #5: Third party insurance (bought on broker's/TA's website) will only cover You AFTER You pay for the excess, and depending on Your rate, it can be up to vehicle's full cost! Also, not before they get all of the documentation from the rental company, and sometimes that documentation - like police reports, take up to a year to obtain, depending on country.

My general advice - always book as early as You can and don't fall for the rental price alone. Read T&C and compare prices of additional equipment and services. Doesn't matter if You've booked through broker (rentalcars, kayak, etc) or directly with rental company, always communicate with the end provider to have written proof of all of the rates, and services You're not obliged to pay.

As someone who worked for Enterprise in an airport. 1) Only some of the counter people make commission. As a customer service agent yes under Alamo and National(both owned by Enterprise) but as an Management Trainee or higher position we do not make commission at all however we do need a certain percentage of tickets to qualify at the end if the month. 2) I recommend renting through the actual website only because I had at least 10ppl a day have some kind of travel issue or problem with the reservation and we could not do much on our end, they had to crawl thru hoops calling the 3rd parties they booked for to get anything fixed, they also don't always tell you or inform of some other fees such as a local security deposits or policies that might require additional documentation that can prevent someone from getting a vehicle depending on the location. 3) At least with Enterprise the prepaid fuel is cheaper than any of the gas stations with a 10mile radius of the airport by at least 15cents as we have someone who daily checks the flutuations of the gas market and adjust our area accordingly. 4)The National emerald club is definitely worth it in certain locations like Atlanta and Las Vegas as you do get a different selection of vehicles higher in the ranks while only paying for the midsized car rate. For example a Camaro SS for the price of a Corolla and the program is free. Also depending on the location and number of available cars Emerald club members were given priority to available vehicles, by some employees, they also get the newest sometimes straight off the truck vehicles with 5 miles, and free upgrades to luxury vehicles

When it comes to prepaid fuel, it's best to buy it if you're off airport and returning to an airport. Fuel near off airport is cheaper than it will be when you get to the airport. If you have the car for several days, in 2022, you never know what the gas prices will be like next week. So if you prepaid for the fuel, you got a deal if price shoots up again. Especially during holidays.

In regards to 3rd party insurance, I work for Hertz, and I can promise that our Loss Damage Waiver (LDW) is a much better option than that $10.99 Collision Damage Waiver (CDW) and here is why. Our LDW will cover the rental car 100%, bumper to bumper, regardless of fault, with a zero deductible, including theft. There is a reason the CDW is  called a COLLISION damage Waiver. It only protects you in the event of a collision. Maybe theft. But is usually does not cover 100% of the vehicle. And you personal insurance will only cover up to the amount in your policy. So if your policy covers $25000 and you rent a $80000 suv, if you total that suv, you're responsible for that remaining $55000 out of pocket. It's always best to take our LDW if your traveling far, poor weather, in a college/party town, during major travel/holiday seasons, or when in an unfamiliar area.

Tips: 
Credit cards often cover rental insurance.

If possible, book in a state/city with less or no sales tax. Example, Portland vs. Seattle. No sales tax in Oregon. This especially adds up if booking for weeks.

Foreign websites like Chinese ones often have better deals. Obviously you’ll be using the ones that offer English. Ctrip is one

When booking, it’s often smart to use the “Free upgrade” coupon on days that you know cars will be limited. This helps guarantee you’ll get an awesome luxury or SUV upgrade. Booking intermediate level cars for a few dollars more, plus the upgrade coupon is a good strategy.

Booking for a month is often as cheap as booking for 3 weeks (sometimes 2), because of monthly discount.

Rental Car Reps do not make incentives or commission for additional products or services. Also, if you use 3rd party coverage you still will need to file a claim and pay your deductible. The 3rd party will reimburse the cost of the deductible. Thank you!

Also, if something happens and they run out of cars, reservations through 3rd parties are much more likely to get turned away than someone who booked through the company itself.  And when it comes to insurance, some states haves laws that make so the rental agency doesn’t have to deal with 3rd party insurance.  Meaning you will get charged for any damages and then have to get the 3rd party insurance to reimburse you.

So, I've got a quick, useful story to add regarding credit card coverage (collision damage waiver). I am American, but I live and work overseas. While visiting family in the States, I rented a car at LAX and used one of my Bank of America Visa credit cards to pay for it. It had the collision damage waiver benefit for rental cars, so I didn't get any additional insurance on top of that. The following day, in rural California, I hit a deer that suddenly ran onto the freeway. Fortunately we were all safe in the vehicle, but the front of the car was an absolute mess. Very long story short, I eventually received a bill from a collections company for well over $10k!! (The car had likely been written off/ auctioned off.) After months of talking with Visa's Card Benefits Services and sending all types of paperwork and documentation,  Visa negotiated a settlement with the collections agency, and I ended up paying $0! In fact, I was surprised to learn that Visa's fine print (for my specific card) even permitted me to receive full reimbursement for the towing charges I had paid out of pocket the day of the accident ($250+). Obviously,  I was tremendously grateful. All the fine print for my card ended up working in my favor in this specific situation. Here are lessons I learned  that I will pass on to you: Read the fine print of the benefits that come with your specific card!!! Find out if there are limits to coverage, such as the number of days you'll be renting a car AND type of coverage offered by the card (secondary or primary). Check on coverage for domestic rentals vs. international rentals. If you accept any insurance from the rental car company or a third party (which I am not discouraging whatsoever here), just be aware that your credit card benefit might not cover you in the same way. Obviously,  I'm very fortunate nobody was hurt AND no other vehicles or people were involved in the accident. That certainly could have changed the financial outcome dramatically. Again, read the fine print... I'd even encourage you to take ten minutes to call your Card Benefit Services to ask questions about the coverage they provide.

So I know this video is getting a little old and if I’m upfront I use to mange a very highly reputable car rental location in an airport. Some tips for your next video:
1. Insurance is worth the cost if you are taking the car a far distance and or thru a place with more intense weather climates such as snow. You are not liable for any damage and it saves people a lot of hassle. 
2. Booking thru 3rd party’s will often go off without a hitch, no doubt, find your deals, but by doing this, you are not guaranteed a car and if you buy their 3rd party insurance, the car rental company will contact you and not the third party insurance. you are made a middle man to get the car fixed. I have seen many of people become very frustrated with the process.
3. A lot of rental systems will register an error and a manager will be involved if too many discounts are being applied. The counter should be able to override it for customer service reasons, but when it comes to making money, they will make you pay the difference and tell you to book straight thru the company website next time to get a more accurate price. Again, the company does not have to adhere to the price of your third party booking. And if you have a problem with that, they will tell you to contact that third party, only for you to then get lucky enough to get a refund from said third party and pay the normal rental price anyway. 
4. As he says at the end, ALWAYS get a receipt when you return the car. It is the job of the rental company to add fees before you leave and it is illegal for them to add anything after the rental is fully returned so get your proof.
Ps. You should see that 200 dollar extra processing hold on your card released back within a week and call your bank if it’s not. If you call the rental company about it, they will just tell you to call the bank because it gets released from the systems the next calendar day after return.

Disclaimer. I am a former car rental manager. On several websites I have given my assistance to people in finding the best deal. I have even consulted with the owner of Autoslash when he was first starting. And I have the emails to prove it. Overall, your six tips were 100% spot on. I do have a 7th for you. Yes, you will always save money by prepaying for a rental. And yes, rental agents do make much of their money from add-ons. But there are some add-ons that have value, and there are some ways that rental agents make money that you didn't mention. Let me go through my number seven for you. 

Car rental agents make money from walk-ups as well. I left the car rental industry in 2007. And since then I have never paid a car rental at the lowest advertised rate utilizing any of the websites. I have beaten it, often significantly.  This also works to get a better class of car than you paid for as well.

 I have this process: I book the lowest refundable rate I can find. I make sure that it's 100% refundable and that I will not have any issues if I no-show. Then when I land, with a printed copy of my rate, I will walk to all the rental companies located on the airport. I will walk up to the agent and say "can you beat this?" 95% of the time I will get an agent that will find me a cheaper rate because that walk up traffic is a commission walking out the door.  Now this will not work if you have a reservation and you try to walk up to the same company that you hold a reservation for. So you need to make sure you have one safety reservation is what I call it at a rate that you can live with. Let's say that company is Avis. When you arrive at the airport you check Hertz, national, Alamo, advantage, Fox, budget or any other rental car company to see if they can beat that rate. If they don't, you stick with your safety reservation. If they do, and almost every single time they do at least give you added value for the same price, you can opt to stay or take the better rate. 

The 5% of the time that I do not get a better rate or get the same rate, it's because they are sold out in the entire airport, which is all too common right now.  However in Las Vegas in early May, I was able to secure a rate $15 per day less than my reservation with this same process. 

There is one circumstance where using the website of the rental company is useful. If the company that you work for or the association that you are a member of has a discount, you need to at least investigate what that discount will get you. For example, if you need to pay for a second driver, many discounts will make that second driver free, include collision damage waiver insurance, include a free tank of gas, or provide other benefits on top of a discount. Your mileage may quite literally vary, but if you pay $15 a day more using a company rate then auto slash can give you, but it includes full insurance, additional drivers, it allows you a free tank of gas, you might very well come out significantly ahead. For example, it's been many years but there was a marketing company that had a negotiated rate with the company that I worked for. LDW first $5,000 was covered by the company rate, additional drivers were free, the rate also allowed the use of a debit card without additional fees, also allowed underage drivers without an additional fee. To top it all off, the rate also allowed them to return the gas at any level with no charge. But they were paying a flat $50 per day unlimited mileage. In some cities, New York for example, $50 per day at that time was fantastic. But in the off season in Hawaii, cars could be had as cheap as $15 per day. But an additional driver, underage driver, insurance would add $75 per day, you can see where the company and anyone using that code who was authorized could significantly save money.

I don't rent cars often but when I do, I take pictures of the odometer and the inside and exterior of the car when I return it.  If you go to pick-up the car, check it for damages and cleanliness, if you see ANYTHING not recorded on the contract, notify the desk of the damage and photograph it make sure it's documented.  If you will be picking it up or returning it in the dark a flashlight to check for damages is a good idea, your phone has a good one.  New damage may have been done since the last return by another driver in the lot or even the person who moved it around in the lot or filled the tank.  Better to have pictures to delete later than to have damage you have to pay for. “I never thought of myself as mean” Not even when you were bullying other students in the first movie? Why has everyone forgotten how bad she was in the first film? Even Ben’s parents didn’t like her.

Audrey says, and I am paraphrasing; I cannot handle another second of pretending to be something I am not. I have obeyed all the rules and never asked for anything that wasn't mine. Therefore, why did Ben fall in love with Mal and not me? That really hurt me. 

There is so much to unpack there, I don't know where to begin. 

There are plenty of fish in the sea. Ben decided that Mal is his ideal woman. I am sure that somewhere out there, there is a man who would love you as much as Ben loves Mal. 

It is great that you obeyed the rules and never asked for anything that wasn't your's. However, that does not entitle you to Ben's affection or the title of queen. The only thing you are entitled to for behaving like a decent person is being able to reasonably expect others to treat you with the same respect.

Mostly accurate, just a few observations:

Secret #2: The rental rate may not always be as attractive as going through broker, but usually T&C are much more relaxed and prices of additional equipment and services are much lower. Depending on Your needs, renting directly through provider can be cheaper. Rental companies have their own reservation teams, don't be afraid to ask them anything, email is the best way of communication.

Secret #5: Third party insurance (bought on broker's/TA's website) will only cover You AFTER You pay for the excess, and depending on Your rate, it can be up to vehicle's full cost! Also, not before they get all of the documentation from the rental company, and sometimes that documentation - like police reports, take up to a year to obtain, depending on country.

My general advice - always book as early as You can and don't fall for the rental price alone. Read T&C and compare prices of additional equipment and services. Doesn't matter if You've booked through broker (rentalcars, kayak, etc) or directly with rental company, always communicate with the end provider to have written proof of all of the rates, and services You're not obliged to pay.

As someone who worked for Enterprise in an airport. 1) Only some of the counter people make commission. As a customer service agent yes under Alamo and National(both owned by Enterprise) but as an Management Trainee or higher position we do not make commission at all however we do need a certain percentage of tickets to qualify at the end if the month. 2) I recommend renting through the actual website only because I had at least 10ppl a day have some kind of travel issue or problem with the reservation and we could not do much on our end, they had to crawl thru hoops calling the 3rd parties they booked for to get anything fixed, they also don't always tell you or inform of some other fees such as a local security deposits or policies that might require additional documentation that can prevent someone from getting a vehicle depending on the location. 3) At least with Enterprise the prepaid fuel is cheaper than any of the gas stations with a 10mile radius of the airport by at least 15cents as we have someone who daily checks the flutuations of the gas market and adjust our area accordingly. 4)The National emerald club is definitely worth it in certain locations like Atlanta and Las Vegas as you do get a different selection of vehicles higher in the ranks while only paying for the midsized car rate. For example a Camaro SS for the price of a Corolla and the program is free. Also depending on the location and number of available cars Emerald club members were given priority to available vehicles, by some employees, they also get the newest sometimes straight off the truck vehicles with 5 miles, and free upgrades to luxury vehicles

When it comes to prepaid fuel, it's best to buy it if you're off airport and returning to an airport. Fuel near off airport is cheaper than it will be when you get to the airport. If you have the car for several days, in 2022, you never know what the gas prices will be like next week. So if you prepaid for the fuel, you got a deal if price shoots up again. Especially during holidays.

In regards to 3rd party insurance, I work for Hertz, and I can promise that our Loss Damage Waiver (LDW) is a much better option than that $10.99 Collision Damage Waiver (CDW) and here is why. Our LDW will cover the rental car 100%, bumper to bumper, regardless of fault, with a zero deductible, including theft. There is a reason the CDW is  called a COLLISION damage Waiver. It only protects you in the event of a collision. Maybe theft. But is usually does not cover 100% of the vehicle. And you personal insurance will only cover up to the amount in your policy. So if your policy covers $25000 and you rent a $80000 suv, if you total that suv, you're responsible for that remaining $55000 out of pocket. It's always best to take our LDW if your traveling far, poor weather, in a college/party town, during major travel/holiday seasons, or when in an unfamiliar area.

Tips: 
Credit cards often cover rental insurance.

If possible, book in a state/city with less or no sales tax. Example, Portland vs. Seattle. No sales tax in Oregon. This especially adds up if booking for weeks.

Foreign websites like Chinese ones often have better deals. Obviously you’ll be using the ones that offer English. Ctrip is one

When booking, it’s often smart to use the “Free upgrade” coupon on days that you know cars will be limited. This helps guarantee you’ll get an awesome luxury or SUV upgrade. Booking intermediate level cars for a few dollars more, plus the upgrade coupon is a good strategy.

Booking for a month is often as cheap as booking for 3 weeks (sometimes 2), because of monthly discount.

Rental Car Reps do not make incentives or commission for additional products or services. Also, if you use 3rd party coverage you still will need to file a claim and pay your deductible. The 3rd party will reimburse the cost of the deductible. Thank you!

So, I've got a quick, useful story to add regarding credit card coverage (collision damage waiver). I am American, but I live and work overseas. While visiting family in the States, I rented a car at LAX and used one of my Bank of America Visa credit cards to pay for it. It had the collision damage waiver benefit for rental cars, so I didn't get any additional insurance on top of that. The following day, in rural California, I hit a deer that suddenly ran onto the freeway. Fortunately we were all safe in the vehicle, but the front of the car was an absolute mess. Very long story short, I eventually received a bill from a collections company for well over $10k!! (The car had likely been written off/ auctioned off.) After months of talking with Visa's Card Benefits Services and sending all types of paperwork and documentation,  Visa negotiated a settlement with the collections agency, and I ended up paying $0! In fact, I was surprised to learn that Visa's fine print (for my specific card) even permitted me to receive full reimbursement for the towing charges I had paid out of pocket the day of the accident ($250+). Obviously,  I was tremendously grateful. All the fine print for my card ended up working in my favor in this specific situation. Here are lessons I learned  that I will pass on to you: Read the fine print of the benefits that come with your specific card!!! Find out if there are limits to coverage, such as the number of days you'll be renting a car AND type of coverage offered by the card (secondary or primary). Check on coverage for domestic rentals vs. international rentals. If you accept any insurance from the rental car company or a third party (which I am not discouraging whatsoever here), just be aware that your credit card benefit might not cover you in the same way. Obviously,  I'm very fortunate nobody was hurt AND no other vehicles or people were involved in the accident. That certainly could have changed the financial outcome dramatically. Again, read the fine print... I'd even encourage you to take ten minutes to call your Card Benefit Services to ask questions about the coverage they provide.

Booking thru 3rd party’s will often go off without a hitch, no doubt, find your deals, but by doing this, you are not guaranteed a car and if you buy their 3rd party insurance, the car rental company will contact you and not the third party insurance. you are made a middle man to get the car fixed. I have seen many of people become very frustrated with the process.
3. A lot of rental systems will register an error and a manager will be involved if too many discounts are being applied. The counter should be able to override it for customer service reasons, but when it comes to making money, they will make you pay the difference and tell you to book straight thru the company website next time to get a more accurate price. Again, the company does not have to adhere to the price of your third party booking. And if you have a problem with that, they will tell you to contact that third party, only for you to then get lucky enough to get a refund from said third party and pay the normal rental price anyway. 
4. As he says at the end, ALWAYS get a receipt when you return the car. It is the job of the rental company to add fees before you leave and it is illegal for them to add anything after the rental is fully returned so get your proof.
Ps. You should see that 200 dollar extra processing hold on your card released back within a week and call your bank if it’s not. If you call the rental company about it, they will just tell you to call the bank because it gets released from the systems the next calendar day after return.

Disclaimer. I am a former car rental manager. On several websites I have given my assistance to people in finding the best deal. I have even consulted with the owner of Autoslash when he was first starting. And I have the emails to prove it. Overall, your six tips were 100% spot on. I do have a 7th for you. Yes, you will always save money by prepaying for a rental. And yes, rental agents do make much of their money from add-ons. But there are some add-ons that have value, and there are some ways that rental agents make money that you didn't mention. Let me go through my number seven for you. 

Car rental agents make money from walk-ups as well. I left the car rental industry in 2007. And since then I have never paid a car rental at the lowest advertised rate utilizing any of the websites. I have beaten it, often significantly.  This also works to get a better class of car than you paid for as well.

 I have this process: I book the lowest refundable rate I can find. I make sure that it's 100% refundable and that I will not have any issues if I no-show. Then when I land, with a printed copy of my rate, I will walk to all the rental companies located on the airport. I will walk up to the agent and say "can you beat this?" 95% of the time I will get an agent that will find me a cheaper rate because that walk up traffic is a commission walking out the door.  Now this will not work if you have a reservation and you try to walk up to the same company that you hold a reservation for. So you need to make sure you have one safety reservation is what I call it at a rate that you can live with. Let's say that company is Avis. When you arrive at the airport you check Hertz, national, Alamo, advantage, Fox, budget or any other rental car company to see if they can beat that rate. If they don't, you stick with your safety reservation. If they do, and almost every single time they do at least give you added value for the same price, you can opt to stay or take the better rate. 

The 5% of the time that I do not get a better rate or get the same rate, it's because they are sold out in the entire airport, which is all too common right now.  However in Las Vegas in early May, I was able to secure a rate $15 per day less than my reservation with this same process. 

There is one circumstance where using the website of the rental company is useful. If the company that you work for or the association that you are a member of has a discount, you need to at least investigate what that discount will get you. For example, if you need to pay for a second driver, many discounts will make that second driver free, include collision damage waiver insurance, include a free tank of gas, or provide other benefits on top of a discount. Your mileage may quite literally vary, but if you pay $15 a day more using a company rate then auto slash can give you, but it includes full insurance, additional drivers, it allows you a free tank of gas, you might very well come out significantly ahead. For example, it's been many years but there was a marketing company that had a negotiated rate with the company that I worked for. LDW first $5,000 was covered by the company rate, additional drivers were free, the rate also allowed the use of a debit card without additional fees, also allowed underage drivers without an additional fee. To top it all off, the rate also allowed them to return the gas at any level with no charge. But they were paying a flat $50 per day unlimited mileage. In some cities, New York for example, $50 per day at that time was fantastic. But in the off season in Hawaii, cars could be had as cheap as $15 per day. But an additional driver, underage driver, insurance would add $75 per day, you can see where the company and anyone using that code who was authorized could significantly save money.

I don't rent cars often but when I do, I take pictures of the odometer and the inside and exterior of the car when I return it.  If you go to pick-up the car, check it for damages and cleanliness, if you see ANYTHING not recorded on the contract, notify the desk of the damage and photograph it make sure it's documented.  If you will be picking it up or returning it in the dark a flashlight to check for damages is a good idea, your phone has a good one.  New damage may have been done since the last return by another driver in the lot or even the person who moved it around in the lot or filled the tank.  Better to have pictures to delete later than to have damage you have to pay for.   One last thing, check the trunk, and under the seats for trash, last time I renter there was some trash in both places.  $1.00 or 2 at a car wash vacuum is much less than they will charge you.
BTW these apply to trailers or vans rented for moving.

میری طرح بہت سے پاکستانی بھائی سعودی عرب میں کام کر اپنا کاروبار کر رہے تھے اور سعودی گورنمنٹ کی سعودائیزیشن پالیسی اور آخر میں کاروبار کو کورونا بھران دھکا کھا کر اب کاروبار اور پیسہ سب نقصانات میں گنوا کے خالی ہاتھ اور بے یار و مدد گار اب یہاں پریشان بیٹھے ہیں  ہمارے پاس کوئی نہ کوئی ہنر ہر کسی کے پاس ہے  آپ لوگ ہمیں پاکستان میں اپنی ان نئی فیکٹریوں میں یا کہیں کام کا موقع فراہم کریں یا چھوٹے پیداواری یونٹ لگانے میں مدد کی جائے تاکہ ھم لوگ یہاں پر ذلیل ہونے سے بچ جائیں اور ہمارے بچے جو کہ اب ھماری معاشی تنگی کی وجہ سے پاکستان بھیج دئیے تھے وہ بھی وہاں پر پریشان ھونے سے بچ جائیں ۔   ھم لوگ یہاں اقامة بھی ختم کر کے اب اس خوف میں مبتلاء ہیں کہ پاکستان بھیج دئیے گئے تو وہاں کچھ نہ کر سکیں گے  وہاں تو ہر انسان مہنگائی اور بے روزگاری کا رونا رو رہا ہے  تو ھمارا کیا ھو گا ۔  براہ کرم حکومت اور فلاحی اداروں کی اس طرف خاص توجہ کروائی جائے۔  یہ مستقبل قریب میں ایک بہت بڑا قومی المیہ بن کر سامنے آنے والا ھے۔   خدارا ان لوگوں کا کچھ سوچیں۔

Even the EY Analysis doesn't quite make the point that EVs ultimately result in less money leaving our shores.  It is partially accounted for in their Income tax effects

"To quantify the income taxation impact from
additional electricity generation and spending
diversion from fuel retailing to the broader
economy"
But I believe there is more benefit than this because a significant portion of the spend on fuel leaves our shores - we import in excess of $30 billion worth of petrol and oil each year.   I don't believe the net benefit of the improved balance of trade that results when we reduce imported fuels is really covered by the EY analysis.  They are just saying people have a bit more money to spend on something else.  I am no economist, but it makes sense to reduce the amount of money that leaves our shores and when you do there must be some sort of additional economic benefit.  And whilst EVs are more expensive, this is due to batteries - and which nation is one of the biggest Lithium suppliers?  And whilst EVs are imported and are more expensive - they will last longer.

I think it's pretty reasonable to accept that EVs should pay some amount of money for their usage of roads and public infrastructure, whilst also wanting this amount to be proportionally less according to their emissions. Your main point here seems to be that EVs should be subsidised more in Australia, which is something I wholeheartedly agree with, but I feel that a more measured approach to your points in the first part of the video would have been welcome, rather than attacking the concept of an tax entirely.

Here is a good article by academics on the subject, https://theconversation.com/think-taxing-electric-vehicle-use-is-a-backward-step-heres-why-its-an-important-policy-advance-150644

As they say, it's the upfront costs of EVs that are the current barrier to adoption, and these new taxes will not noticeably move the needle on that rate of adoption. In my view, our energy should be spent pushing for subsidies for this part of the process first and foremost.

If the green car was cheaper than the gasoline car, and drivers replaced at the same rate as today (100M/yr), we could convert the existing fleet (2.5B total) in 25 years without asking drivers to spend more money, which they would probably accept.
To beat gas, we can explore cheap green liquid ammonia that powers fuel cells, which produces electricity, which turns motors, which turns wheels. And we can also explore standardized swappable low-range cheap plug-in EV batteries that use fewer rare earth materials.
Liquid ammonia has three big challenges: (a) it consumes three times more volume relative to gasoline per unit energy, (b) it needs to be chilled to -33°C, and (c) ammonia vapor needs to be kept out of noses. To maintain refrigeration, ammonia-based vehicles would need to maintain constant communication with a central authority, and if refrigeration failed, a service vehicle would need to visit to either repair or remove ammonia. A plug-in swappable standard refrigeration hardware unit used by all vehicles might make automated replacement easier. A refrigeration maintenance system would ultimately add to the total cost of ownership. 
The good news is that liquid ammonia fuel made with Generation 4 should be cheaper than gasoline, per unit energy. And a fuel cell's 50% efficiency is better than an internal combustion engine's 25% efficiency. Also, one can explore combusting hydrogen, as explained in this video. In summary, if engineers can get the total cost of ownership for an ammonia-based car to be less than a gasoline-based car, it might be viable.
Currently, proprietary batteries are installed in each EV car and are periodically charged. Alternatively, one could have a standard plug-in battery, where all cars use the same form, and are swapped with a fresh battery in less than 60 seconds. Car owners would pay for the energy consumed and wear on the battery. Cavities would be dug out at key locations and a mechanism would be dropped in via crane that implements charging, storage and swap. Cars would position themselves over the mechanism, and the swap would occur automatically. Swap mechanisms might be positioned next to highway on/off ramps, and next to frequented establishments. For example, the corner next to your local drug store might be convenient. If swap is easy and fast, then shorter range batteries would become more acceptable; and these tend to be cheaper and use fewer rare earth materials.
Installing swap chambers or liquid ammonia refueling infrastructure would be an enormous undertaking. 
Currently, gov't observes that EV battery prices have dropped over the past few years, extrapolates forward, and declares this as the transportation decarbonization plan. However, this might not work due to rare earth constraints. Subsequently, we should consider investing heavily in transportation that is cheaper than gas and is not resource constrained. For example, gov't could invest $10M/yr over 3 years for each of the following R&D initiatives:
•	Design swappable plug-in battery infrastructure. 
•	Design ammonia-based car.
•	Design an automated ammonia refueling station.
•	Design a standardized plug-in ammonia refrigeration unit & tank.
•	Design an automated city-wide ammonia refrigeration monitoring and maintenance system.
In summary, engineers need to figure out how to build 2,500,000 cheap green cars over ~25 years.

I'm rather skeptical about EV's in general. Here in the UK (and much of Europe) we tend to travel relatively short distances and you're never far from a town or City, but when I look at the cost of buying an electric car it's WAY beyond my normal budget. The car I've got now cost me £7,800 which is the most I have EVER spent on a car; my last car was £3,500 (5 years of driving without trouble, and I sold it only because it was looking shabby) the one before that was £1,600 and the one before that was £900. 

I don't mind  a couple of dings and scratches on a car so I'd be happy enough buying a used EV, but regardless of cosmetics, the big thing about any EV is the _battery._ It loses range as it ages. Sure, from new it might - I'll pick on the Nissan Leaf for the sake or argument - as Nissan claims of the Nissan Leaf be good for 100,000 miles, but it will lose about 1/3rd of it's range long before that; and the Nissan Leaf doesn't exactly have long range to start with - around 90 miles on a full charge. Okay, that'll easily get me to work and back, but what about when the car is a little older? I commute 20 miles each way to work; I _should_ be okay on a 60 mile range, but it only leaves me 20 miles to spare so I'd better hope I don't have to take a diversion or I need to take the car out again the same day. 

The Nissan Leaf without a subsidy costs £26,000 for the most basic short-range model. £26,000? That's an awful of money. I'm spending maybe £1200 per year on fuel (plus oil - another £100 or so) so over 10 years I'd save - ignoring the cost of charging an EV - £12,000. So we can call the real price of the EV £14,000. That's still £10,000 more than I would spend on a vehicle and I would not be able to trust it to get me to work when it was over 7 years old. I wonder what the resale value is on a 10 year old EV? 

If I HAD to buy an electric car today, I could do it, but it would wipe out my meager finances and I don't know how I'd afford one in the future. 

I also wonder about the true costs if and when EV's take over. I think EV fanboys are deluding themselves that the cost of charging an EV will remain cheap. If the Government can't recoup the massive tax revenues of petrol and diesel directly from EV's, they'll take it from us indirectly. To do an apples to apples comparison, petrol in the UK in 2015 was 32.4p per litre before tax and £1.08 after tax. https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2979083/Britain-one-lowest-petrol-prices-Europe-tax-highest-VAT-duty-added.html
About 65% of the cost is tax. 

Is there ANY chance the Government won't want that money? They'll take it by hook or by crook. 

I don't want to rain on EV's too much; ICE cars have all kinds of practical issues too, and I am hoping that EV's become affordable - the same price as ICE cars. But I don't see how batteries will ever be cheap enough unless a whole new futuristic technology is developed.

My paternal grandparents made beer and wine in their basement.  Well, actually, my grandmother made the beer and wine from recipes passed down through her family.  My grandfather owned a produce store so he could supply my grandmother whatever she needed.  The local ice cream truck driver supplied the empty root beer bottles for my grandmother to bottle the beer and wine in.  My dad recalled hearing “pop-pop-pop” noises at 1 AM from the beer bottles that were over-carbonated.

It was a great business model.  My grand father could write off whatever produce was used as spoilage, the ice cream man sold adult root beer as well as kids root beer so everything was listed as root beer.  No doubt they supplied some local speakeasies.  My grandmother even had a potato beer recipe.

🔍 *سن ھجری سے عیسوی اور عیسوی سے ھجری سن بنانے کا طریقہ* 🔎

*اکثر قدیم کتابوں میں سنہ ھجری  کا ہوتا ہے اور عام لوگوں کو اس وقت کا عیسوی سنہ معلوم کرنادشوار ہوتاہے اس لئے عیسوی سنہ معلوم کرنے کا فارمولہ یا طریقہ شیر کرتا ہوں:*

*(1) سن ھجری کو پہلے 33پر تقسیم کیاجائے.*

*(2) حاصل قسمت کو اسی ھجری سن سےمنفی کیا جائے.*

*(3) جو جواب ائے اس کے ساتھ622 جمع کیا جائے(پہلے ھجری کے وقت عیسوی سنہ 622تھا).*

*(4) اس طر622 جمع کرنے کے بعد جو جواب یا ھندسہ ائےگا وہ عیسوی سن ھوگا.*
*مثلا 1200ھ سے عیسوی سنہ اس طرح بنایا جائے گا:*
1200÷33=36
1200-36=1164
1164+622=1786

*اسطرح 1200ھ 1786کے برار ہے یعنی اس وقت عیسوی سنہ 1786 تھی*

*ھجری سن معلوم کرنا:*
ھجری=(عیسوی سن -622)×33÷32
مثلا 2018 کا ھجری= (2018-622)×33÷32
2018-622=1396
1396×33=46068
46068÷32=1439
1439ھ یعنی 2018 میں ھجری 1439
یا 1200ھ
Hijri = (AD- 622) x 33 ÷ 32

For example: AD = 1786
Hijri = 1786 - 622 = 1164
        = 1164 x 33 = 38412
        = 38412 ÷ 32 
        = 1200

1) Best for climate is to use your car as long as you can if it works fine and not buy new vehicle, because you are just increasing the number of cars on the road, there is no disposal process in Pak and hence this policy will just make people buy more cars and dump their old cars to other people and increase over all consumption and pollution.

2)Electric vehicles are very performance based, in a country where number of accidents have increased so much recently because of speed being more accessible this cannot be a good news.

3)Electric vehicle require expensive maintenance once they do have an issue, they are reliable until they are not, electricity needs to be stable, I run a computer repair centre and the amount of burnt chargers we get is very high, same could be expected for EVs, they will have charging issues because our grid is outdated.

4)A transition period should promote hybrid vehicles instead of full EV vehicles, we see that already JDM hybrids have took over market but except Prius I am not aware of any other local selling hybrid.

This policy is just another 'good looks' policy which will be very hard to implement when you see the ground reality.

Will just bring more harm than good.

This was the same issue when plastic bags were banned, my argument was often that first a disposal system should be implemented for plastic waste instead of straight banning them. Now you have plastic and cloth based bags polluting the streets instead of just plastic.

I see the same happened with EVs, instead of going green, the vehicles will just double on the road and leave a bigger impact.
